<section xml:id="sect-other-rootfinding">
  <title>Other Rootfinding Methods</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      In <xref ref="sect-newtons-method"/>, we saw Newton's method.
      Although it's not a perfect rootfinding algorithm, Newton's method has a lot of strength including it's relative simplicity and quadratic convergence.
      However, one drawback is that it requires taking the derivative.
      In this chapter we will see the secant method which uses a secant line instead of a tangent line to estimate the root.
    </p>

    <p>
      Additional methods including the blending of the methods we've seen including using the speed of Newton's method with the bisection method which guarantees a root.
    </p>
  </introduction>


  <subsection xml:id="subsec-secant-method">
    <title>The Secant Method</title>

    <p>
      Recall that in <xref ref="sect-newtons-method"/>, we used the tangent line to the function <m>f(x)</m> to estimate the root.
      If instead, we use the secant line, we do the same.
      <xref ref="fig-secant-method"/> shows the secant line through a function <m>y=f(x)</m> through two points <m>(x_1, f(x_1))</m> and <m>(x_2, f(x_2))</m>.
      The zero of the secant line is found and labelled as <m>x_3</m>.
      This is used recursively.
    </p>

    <figure xml:id="fig-secant-method">
      <caption></caption>
      <image width="75%">
        <shortdescription>
        </shortdescription>
        <latex-image>
          <![CDATA[ 
          \begin{tikzpicture}[scale =2]
            \draw[->] (-1,0) -- (5,0) node [above right] {$x$};
            \draw[->] (0,-3) -- (0,3); 
            \draw[<->] plot [domain=-0.5:4] (\x,{0.3*(\x-1.25)^2-0.5});
            \draw (3,0.1) -- (3,-0.1) node [below] {$x_2$};
            \draw (4,0.1) -- (4,-0.1) node [below] {$x_1$};
            \fill (3,{0.3*(3-1.25)^2-0.5}) circle (1pt);
            \fill (4,{0.3*(4-1.25)^2-0.5}) circle (1pt);
            \draw ({(0.5-0.3*(3-1.25)^2)/(0.3*((4-1.25)^2-(3-1.25)^2))+ 3},0.1) 
            -- ({(0.5-0.3*(3-1.25)^2)/(0.3*((4-1.25)^2-(3-1.25)^2))+ 3},-0.1) node [below] {$x_3$};
            \draw plot[domain =2:4.25] (\x, {(0.3*((4-1.25)^2-(3-1.25)^2))*(\x-3)+0.3*(3-1.25)^2-0.5});
          \end{tikzpicture}
          ]]>
        </latex-image>
      </image>
    </figure>

    <p>
      Recall that a secant line through the points <m>(x_1, f(x_1))</m> and <m>(x_2, f(x_2))</m> can be written
      <me>
        y = f(x_2) + \frac{f(x_2)-f(x_1)}{x_2-x_1} (x - x_2)
      </me>
      and the zeros of this line is
      <me>
        x = x_2 - f(x_2) \frac{x_2-x_1}{f(x_2)-f(x_1)}
      </me>
      This value is thus used to find an approximation to the root or
      <me>
        x_3 = x_2 - f(x_2) \frac{x_2-x_1}{f(x_2)-f(x_1)}
      </me>
    </p>

    <p>
      If this is same formula is used recursively, then we have
      <men xml:id="eq-secant-step">
        x_{n+1} = x_n - f(x_n) \frac{x_n-x_{n-1}}{f(x_n)-f(x_{n-1})}
      </men>
    </p>

    <algorithm xml:id="alg-secant-method">
      <title>Secant Rootfinding Method</title>

      <statement>
        <p>
          The following will find the root <m>p</m> to within <m>\epsilon</m> using the <term>secant method</term>:
        </p>

        <p>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                Start with two approximations of the root called <m>x_0</m> and <m>x_1</m>.
                Let <m>n=1</m>.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                Find
                <me>
                  x_{n+1} = x_n - f(x_n) \frac{x_n-x_{n-1}}{f(x_n)-f(x_{n-1})}
                </me>
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                If <m>|x_{n+1}-x_n| &lt; \epsilon</m>, stop.
                The best approximation to the root <m>p</m> is <m>x_{n+1}</m>.
                If not, increment <m>n</m> by 1 and return to step 2.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>

        <p>
          Note: An alternative stopping condition would be use <m>|f(x_{n+1})| \lt \epsilon</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </algorithm>

    <p>
      The next example shows the detailed steps to use the secant method.
    </p>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Use the secant method to find the intersection point of <m>y=\cos x</m> and <m>y=x</m> or finding the root of <m>f(x) = \cos x - x</m>.
          This is the same function as in <xref ref="ex-newtons-method"/>.
          Use <m>x_0=1.5</m> and <m>x_1 = 1</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <solution>
        <p>
        </p>

        <table xml:id="table-root-convergence">
          <title>Convergence of Root-Finding Method</title>

          <tabular top="major" left="minor" right="minor" bottom="minor" halign="right">
            <row header="yes" bottom="medium">
              <cell><m>n</m></cell>
              <cell><m>x_n</m></cell>
              <cell><m>f(x_n)</m></cell>
            </row>

            <row>
              <cell>0</cell>
              <cell><m>1.50000000000000000000</m></cell>
              <cell><m>-1.429262798332</m></cell>
            </row>

            <row>
              <cell>1</cell>
              <cell><m>1.00000000000000000000</m></cell>
