          </tabular>
        </table>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>


  <subsection xml:id="subsec-analysis-secant">
    <title>Analysis of the Secant Method</title>

    <p>
      Analyzing the secant method is similar to that of other iterative methods, however, because there are three points involved in the step in <xref ref="eq-secant-step"/>, the analysis must be adapted a bit.
    </p>

    <p>
      First, let <m>p</m> be the root of <m>f</m>, that is, <m>f(p)=0</m> and <m>(x_n)</m> is the sequence of points from the secant method.
      Define <m>\epsilon_n = |x_n-p|</m>.
      Then expand the terms <m>f(x_n)</m> and <m>f(x_{n-1})</m> about the root <m>p</m>.
      <me>
        \begin{aligned} f(x_n) \amp = f(p) + f'(p)(x_n-p) + \frac{f''(p)}{2}(x_n-p)^2 + \cdots \\ \amp = f'(p) \epsilon_n + \frac{f''(p)}{2}\epsilon_n^2 \\ f(x_{n-1})\amp = f(p) + f'(p)(x_{n-1}-p) + \frac{f''(p)}{2}(x_{n-1}-p)^2 + \cdots \\ \amp = f'(p) \epsilon_{n-1} + \frac{f''(p)}{2}\epsilon_{n-1}^2 \end{aligned}
      </me>
      where <m>f(p)=0</m> is used.
      Subtracting these results in
      <me>
        f(x_n) - f(x_{n-1}) = f'(p)(\epsilon_n - \epsilon_{n-1}) + \frac{f''(p)}{2} (\epsilon_n^2 - \epsilon_{n-1}^2)
      </me>
      Then using <xref ref="eq-secant-step"/> and subtracting <m>p</m> from each side results in
      <me>
        \begin{aligned} x_{n+1} - p   \amp = x_n - f(x_n) \frac{x_n-x_{n-1}}{f(x_n)-f(x_{n-1})} - p \\ \epsilon_{n+1}\amp = \epsilon_n - \left(f'(p)\epsilon_n + \frac{f''(p)}{2}\epsilon_n^2\right) \frac{\epsilon_n - \epsilon_{n-1}}{f'(p)(\epsilon_n - \epsilon_{n-1}) + \frac{f''(p)}{2} (\epsilon_n^2 - \epsilon_{n-1}^2)} \\ \amp = \epsilon_n \frac{f'(p)+ \frac{f''(p)}{2} (\epsilon_n + \epsilon_{n-1}) - f'(p) - \epsilon_n f''(p)/2}{f'(p)+ \frac{f''(p)}{2} (\epsilon_n + \epsilon_{n-1})} \\ \amp = \epsilon_n \frac{\epsilon_{n-1} f''(p)/2}{f'(p)+ \frac{f''(p)}{2} (\epsilon_n + \epsilon_{n-1})} \\ \amp \approx \epsilon_n \epsilon_{n-1} \frac{f''(p)}{2f'(p)} \end{aligned}
      </me>
      so we have the relationship that <m>\epsilon_{n+1} \approx C \epsilon_n \epsilon_{n-1}</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
      We are trying to find the order of convergence or the value of <m>\alpha</m> such that <m>\epsilon_{n+1} \approx \lambda \epsilon_n^{\alpha}</m> or equivalently, <m>\epsilon_{n} \approx \lambda \epsilon_{n-1}^{\alpha}</m> which results in
      <me>
        \epsilon_{n-1} \approx \left(\frac{1}{\lambda} \epsilon_n\right)^{1/\alpha}
      </me>
      and then
      <me>
        \begin{aligned} \epsilon_{n+1} \amp \approx C \epsilon_n \epsilon_{n-1} \approx C \epsilon_n \left(\frac{1}{\lambda} \epsilon_n\right)^{1/\alpha} \\ \lambda \epsilon_n^{\alpha} \amp \approx  \frac{C}{\lambda^{1/\alpha}} \epsilon^{1+1/\alpha} \end{aligned}
      </me>
    </p>

    <p>
      To ensure that the powers of <m>\epsilon</m> is the same for both sides:
      <me>
        \begin{aligned} \alpha \amp = 1 + \frac{1}{\alpha} \\ \alpha^2 - \alpha -1 \amp = 0 \end{aligned}
      </me>
      and using the quadratic formula, <m>\alpha = (1 \pm \sqrt{5})/2</m> and since we need <m>\alpha \gt 0</m>, then <m>\alpha  \approx 1.61</m>, the same result that we saw above.
    </p>
  </subsection>


  <subsection xml:id="subsec-newton-bisection">
    <title>The Newton-Bisection Method</title>

    <p>
      One of the advantages of the bisection method from <xref ref="sect-bisection"/> is that if the original interval is guaranteed to contain a root, then each successive step results in a root.
      However, as we saw, it is quite slow to converge and in this section, we combine the speed of Newton's method to speed up the bisection method.
    </p>
  </subsection>


  <subsection xml:id="subsec-mullers-method">
    <title>Muller's Method</title>

    <p>
      Muller's method extends the idea of the secant method to three points and the quadratic that passes through the points.
      Consider a general function as in <xref ref="fig-muller"/>
    </p>

    <figure xml:id="fig-muller">
      <caption></caption>
      <image width="75%">
        <shortdescription>
        </shortdescription>
        <latex-image>
          <![CDATA[ 
          \begin{tikzpicture}[scale =2]
            \draw[->] (-1,0) -- (5,0) node [above right] {$x$};
            \draw[->] (0,-3) -- (0,3); 
            \draw[<->] plot [domain=-0.5:4.5] (\x,{atan(\x-2.2)*pi/180 });
            \draw (1,0.1) -- (1,-0.1) node [below] {$x_2$};
            \draw (3,0.1) -- (3,-0.1) node [below] {$x_1$};
            \draw (4,0.1) -- (4,-0.1) node [below] {$x_0$};
            \fill (3,{atan(3-2.2)*pi/180}) circle (1pt);
            \fill (4,{atan(4-2.2)*pi/180}) circle (1pt);
            \fill (1,{atan(1-2.2)*pi/180}) circle (1pt);
            \draw[<->, blue] plot [domain=0.5:4.5] (\x, {0.6747409422235525 + 0.5177710855896291*(\x-3)-0.12881420541062194*(\x-3)^2});
          \end{tikzpicture}
          ]]>
        </latex-image>
      </image>
    </figure>

    <p>
      We find the parabola that passes through the points <m>(x_0, f_0)</m>, <m>(x_1, f_1)</m> and <m>(x_2, f_2)</m>, where <m>f_j = f(x_j)</m>.
      Although the quadratic can be written in standard form, it is easier if we write it as
      <me>
        q(x) = a_0 + a_1 (x-x_1) + a_2 (x-x_1)^2
      </me>
      We also use
      <me>
        \begin{aligned} h_1 \amp = x_1-x_0 \amp h_2 \amp = x_2 - x_1 \amp \delta_1 \amp = \frac{f_1-f_0}{h_1} \amp \delta_2 \amp = \frac{f_2-f_1}{h_2} \end{aligned}
      </me>
      substituting the three points into <m>q(x)</m> results in
      <md>
        <mrow xml:id="eq-muller-01" number="yes"> q(x_0) \amp =  f_0 = a_0 + a_1 (x_0-x_1) + a_2 (x_0-x_1)^2 = a_0 -a_1 h_1 + a_2 h_1^2 </mrow>
        <mrow xml:id="eq-muller-02" number="yes"> q(x_1) \amp =  f_1 = a_0 </mrow>
        <mrow xml:id="eq-muller-03" number="yes"> q(x_2) \amp =  f_2 = a_0  + a_1 (x_2-x_1) + a_2 (x_2-x_1)^2 = a_0 + a_1 h_2 + a_2 h_2^2 </mrow>
      </md>
      Plugging in <m>a_0=f_1</m> into <xref ref="eq-muller-01"/> and divide by <m>h_1</m> results in
      <men xml:id="eq-muller-04">
        \frac{f_0-f_1}{h_1} = -\delta_1 = - a_1 + a_2 h_1
      </men>
      Combining <xref ref="eq-muller-02"/> and <xref ref="eq-muller-03"/> and dividing by <m>h_2</m> results in
      <men xml:id="eq-muller-05">
        \frac{f_2-f_1}{h_2} = \delta_2 = a_1 + a_2h_2
      </men>
      adding  <xref ref="eq-muller-04"/> and <xref ref="eq-muller-05"/>
      <me>
        \delta_2 - \delta_1 = a_2 (h_1 + h_2)
      </me>
      which results in
      <me>
        a_2 = \frac{\delta_2-\delta_1}{h_1+h_2}
      </me>
      and then subtracting <m>h_2</m> times <xref ref="eq-muller-04"/> and <m>h_1</m> times <xref ref="eq-muller-05"/> results in
      <me>
        \delta_1 h_2 + \delta_2 h_1 = a_1(h_2+h_1)
      </me>
      or
      <me>
        a_1 = \frac{\delta_1 h_2 + \delta_2 h_1 }{h_2+h_1}
      </me>
    </p>

    <p>
      This shows that the quadratic that passes through the points is
      <me>
        q(x) = a_0 + a_1 (x-x_1) + a_2(x-x_1)^2
      </me>
      with
      <me>
        \begin{aligned} a_0 \amp =f_1 \amp a_1 \amp =\frac{\delta_1 h_2 + \delta_2 h_1 }{h_2+h_1} \amp a_2 \amp = \frac{\delta_2-\delta_1}{h_1+h_2} \end{aligned}
      </me>
    </p>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Use the results above to find the quadratic that passes through the points <m>(1,4), (3,1)</m> and <m>(6,2)</m>
        </p>
      </statement>

      <solution>
        <p>
          First,
          <me>
            \begin{aligned} h_1 \amp = x_1 -x_0 = 3-1 = 2  \\ h_2 \amp = x_2 - x_1 = 6-3 = 3 \\ \delta_1 \amp = \frac{f_1-f_0}{h_1} = \frac{1-4}{2} = -\frac{3}{2} \\ \delta_2 \amp = \frac{f_2 -f_1}{h_2} = \frac{2-1}{3} = \frac{1}{3} \end{aligned}
          </me>
          and then the coefficients of the quadratic is
          <me>
            \begin{aligned} a_0 \amp = 1 \\ a_1 \amp = \frac{\delta_1 h_2 + \delta_2 h_1 }{h_2+h_1} = \frac{(-3/2)(3) + (1/3)(2)}{2+3} = -\frac{23}{30} \\ a_2 \amp = \frac{\delta_2-\delta_1}{h_1+h_2} = \frac{(1/3-(-3/2))}{5} = \frac{11}{30} \end{aligned}
          </me>
        </p>

        <p>
          This results in the quadratic equation:
          <me>
            q(x) = 1-\frac{23}{30}(x-3) + \frac{11}{30}(x-3)^2
          </me>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <p>
      Next, Muller's method uses the root of the quadratic to find the root, however, only one of the roots is needed.
      <me>
        x-x_1 = - \frac{2a_0}{a_1 \pm \sqrt{a_1^2-4a_0a_2}} = \frac{-a_1 \pm \sqrt{a_1^2 - 4a_0a_2}}{2 a_2}
      </me>
      The root is the one closer to the point <m>x_2</m> or the one with the larger denominator.
      Thus we will take the sign that is the same as the sign of <m>a_1</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
      Therefore, we get:
      <me>
        x_3 = x_1 -  \frac{2a_0}{a_1 + \text{sgn}(a_1) \sqrt{a_1^2-4a_0a_2}}
      </me>
    </p>

    <algorithm xml:id="alg-muller">
      <statement>
        <p>
          The following steps uses Muller's method to estimate the root <m>p</m> of the function <m>f(x)</m>.
          The input in the function and three <m>x-</m>values.
          Let's call them <m>x_0, x_1</m> and <m>x_2</m> and we will find the root to <c>tol</c>.
        </p>

        <p>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                Store <c>x₀</c>, <c>x₁</c>, <c>x₂</c> in a vector/array.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                Let
                <cd>
                <cline>h₁ = x₁ -x₀</cline>
                <cline>h₂ = x₂ - x₁</cline>
                <cline>δ₁ = (f(x₁)-f(x₀))/h₁</cline>
                <cline>δ₂ = (f(x₂)-f(x₁))/h₂</cline>
                <cline>a₀ = f(x₁)</cline>
                <cline>a₁ = (δ₁ * h₂ + δ₂ * h₁)/(h₁+h₂)</cline>
                <cline>a₂ = (δ₂-δ₁)/(h₁+h₂)</cline>
                </cd>
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                let
                <cd>
                <cline>x₃ = x₁ - 2*a₀/(a₁+sgn(a₁)*sqrt(a₁^2-4*a₂*a₀))</cline>
                </cd>
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                If <c>abs(x₃-x₂) &lt; ϵ</c> then stop and return <c>x₃</c>.
                If not, let
                <cd>
                <cline>x₀ = x₁</cline>
                <cline>x₁ = x₂</cline>
                <cline>x₂ = x₃</cline>
                </cd>
                and return to step 2.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </algorithm>

    <p>
      We will now solve the equation <m>\cos x = x</m> by finding the root of <m>f(x) = \cos x - x</m>.
    </p>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find the root of <m>f(x) = \cos x - x</m> using Muller's method starting with <m>x_0 = 0, x_1 = 1, x_2 = 2</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <solution>
        <p>
          We show the first step in detail and the the remaining ones.
          <cd>
          <cline>h₁ = x₁ -x₀ = 1</cline>
          <cline>h₂ = x₂ - x₁ = 1</cline>
          <cline>δ₁ = (f(x₁)-f(x₀))/h₁ = -1.4596976941</cline>
          <cline>δ₂ = (f(x₂)-f(x₁))/h₂ = -1.9564491424</cline>
          <cline>a₀ = f(x₁) = -0.45969769</cline>
          <cline>a₁ = (δ₁ * h₂ + δ₂ * h₁)/(h₁+h₂) = -1.708073</cline>
          <cline>a₂ = (δ₂-δ₁)/(h₁+h₂) = -0.2483757</cline>
          </cd>
        </p>
        <p>
          And then <c>x₃ =  0.71942008 </c>.
        </p>
        <p>
          We then repeat this until the cutoff value resulting the the following table.  
        </p>
        <table xml:id="table-bigfloat-convergence">
  <title>Root-Finding Convergence with BigFloat</title>
  <tabular top="major" left="minor" right="minor" bottom="minor" halign="right">
    <row header="yes" bottom="medium">
      <cell><alert>n</alert></cell>
      <cell><alert>x</alert></cell>
      <cell><alert>f</alert></cell>
    </row>
    <row header="yes" bottom="minor">
      <cell><m>\text{Int64}</m></cell>
      <cell><m>\text{BigFloat}</m></cell>
      <cell><m>\text{BigFloat}</m></cell>
    </row>
    
    <row><cell>0</cell><cell><m>1.50000000000000000000</m></cell><cell><m>1.000000000000\text{e}{+00}</m></cell></row>
    <row><cell>1</cell><cell><m>1.00000000000000000000</m></cell><cell><m>-4.596976941319\text{e}{-01}</m></cell></row>
    <row><cell>2</cell><cell><m>0.76293613902753061761</m></cell><cell><m>-2.416146836547\text{e}{+00}</m></cell></row>
    <row><cell>3</cell><cell><m>0.74026437750068385814</m></cell><cell><m>3.276790532876\text{e}{-02}</m></cell></row>
